answer:
Definition:
Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language used to develop web, mobile, and desktop applications. It is platform-independent.

Syntax:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Hello Java");
    }
}

Example Output:
Hello Java

Definition:
A variable is a container used to store data.

Syntax:
dataType variableName = value;

Example:
int age = 20;
System.out.println(age);

Definition:
Data types define the type of data stored in a variable.

Syntax:
int a = 10;
float b = 5.5f;
char c = 'A';

Example:
int -> 10
float -> 5.5
char -> 'A'

Definition:
Type casting is converting one data type into another.

Syntax:
int a = (int) 5.5;

Example:
double d = 9.8;
int i = (int) d;
System.out.println(i);

Definition:
Control statements are used to control the flow of execution in a program.

Syntax:
if(condition) {
   // statement
}

Example:
int age = 18;
if(age >= 18) {
    System.out.println("Eligible to vote");
}

Definition:
if-else is used to execute one block if condition is true, otherwise another block.

Syntax:
if(condition) {
   // true block
} else {
   // false block
}

Example:
int num = 10;

if(num % 2 == 0) {
    System.out.println("Even");
} else {
    System.out.println("Odd");
}

Definition:
A loop is used to execute a block of code repeatedly.

Syntax:
for(initialization; condition; increment) {
   // code
}

Example:
for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    System.out.println(i);
}

Definition:
Java provides loops to repeat code execution.

Syntax:
for loop
while loop
do-while loop

Example:
int i = 1;
while(i <= 3) {
    System.out.println(i);
    i++;
}

Definition:
An array is a collection of similar data types stored in a single variable.

Syntax:
dataType[] arrayName = new dataType[size];

Example:
int[] arr = {10, 20, 30};
System.out.println(arr[0]);

Definition:
OOP is a programming style based on objects and classes.

Syntax:
class Demo {
    int a = 10;
}

Example:
class Car {
    String color = "Red";
}

Definition:
A class is a blueprint for creating objects.

Syntax:
class ClassName {
   // variables + methods
}

Example:
class Student {
    int id = 101;
}

Definition:
An object is an instance of a class.

Syntax:
ClassName obj = new ClassName();

Example:
class Student {
    int id = 101;
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
        System.out.println(s.id);
    }
}

Definition:
Encapsulation is wrapping data and methods into a single unit (class).

Syntax:
private int data;
public void setData(int d) {
    data = d;
}

Example:
class Student {
    private int age;

    public void setAge(int a) {
        age = a;
    }

    public void getAge() {
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

Definition:
Inheritance allows a class to acquire properties of another class.

Syntax:
class Child extends Parent {
}

Definition:
Polymorphism means one action can be performed in many ways.

Syntax:
class Demo {
    void show() {}
}

Example (Method Overloading):
class Demo {
    void show(int a) {
        System.out.println(a);
    }

    void show(String b) {
        System.out.println(b);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo d = new Demo();
        d.show(10);
        d.show("Hello");
    }
}

Definition:
Abstraction means hiding implementation details and showing only functionality.

Syntax:
abstract class ClassName {
    abstract void method();
}

Example:
abstract class Animal {
    abstract void sound();
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
}

Definition:
An interface is a blueprint of a class that contains abstract methods.

Syntax:
interface MyInterface {
    void show();
}

Example:
interface Animal {
    void sound();
}

class Dog implements Animal {
    public void sound() {
        System.out.println("Bark");
    }
}

Definition:
Class = Blueprint
Object = Instance of class

Syntax:
class A {}
A obj = new A();

Example:
class Car {
    String color = "Red";
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car c = new Car();
        System.out.println(c.color);
    }
}

Definition:
Overloading = same method name, different parameters
Overriding = same method in parent and child class

Syntax:
// Overloading
void show(int a) {}
void show(String b) {}

Example:
class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Child");
    }
}

Definition:
A constructor is a special method used to initialize objects.

Syntax:
class ClassName {
    ClassName() {
        // constructor code
    }
}

Example:
class Student {
    Student() {
        System.out.println("Constructor called");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student();
    }
}

Definition:
Default constructor
Parameterized constructor

Syntax:
ClassName() {}
ClassName(int a) {}

Example:
class Student {
    Student() {
        System.out.println("Default Constructor");
    }

    Student(int a) {
        System.out.println(a);
    }
}

Definition:
this refers to the current object.

Syntax:
this.variable = variable;

Example:
class Student {
    int age;

    Student(int age) {
        this.age = age;
    }

    void show() {
        System.out.println(age);
    }
}

Definition:
super refers to the parent class object.

Syntax:
super.methodName();

Example:
class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void display() {
        super.show();
    }
}

Definition:
static is used for memory management and shared variables/methods.

Syntax:
static int x = 10;

Example:
class Test {
    static int count = 0;

    Test() {
        count++;
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Test t1 = new Test();
        Test t2 = new Test();
        System.out.println(Test.count);
    }
}

Definition:
Method overloading means multiple methods with the same name but different parameters.

Syntax:
class Demo {
    void show(int a) {}
    void show(String b) {}
}

Example:
class Demo {
    void show(int a) {
        System.out.println(a);
    }

    void show(String b) {
        System.out.println(b);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo d = new Demo();
        d.show(10);
        d.show("Java");
    }
}

Definition:
Method overriding means child class provides specific implementation of parent class method.

Syntax:
class A {
    void show() {}
}

class B extends A {
    void show() {}
}

Example:
class A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Parent class");
    }
}

class B extends A {
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Child class");
    }
}

Definition:
Exception handling is used to handle runtime errors so program does not crash.

Syntax:
try {
    // code
} catch(Exception e) {
    // handling
}

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        try {
            int a = 10 / 0;
        } catch(Exception e) {
            System.out.println("Error occurred");
        }
    }
}

Definition:
Used to handle exceptions in code execution.

Syntax:
try {
    // code
} catch(Exception e) {
    // handling
}

Example:
try {
    int a = 5 / 0;
} catch(Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Cannot divide by zero");
}

Definition:
Finally block always executes whether exception occurs or not.

Syntax:
try {}
catch {}
finally {}

Example:
try {
    int a = 10 / 2;
} catch(Exception e) {
    System.out.println("Error");
} finally {
    System.out.println("Always executed");
}

Definition:
throw is used to manually throw an exception.

Syntax:
throw new Exception();

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        throw new ArithmeticException("Error");
    }
}

Definition:
throws is used to declare exceptions in method signature.

Syntax:
void method() throws Exception {}

Example:
class Demo {
    void show() throws Exception {
        throw new Exception();
    }
}

Definition:
Multithreading is a process of running multiple threads simultaneously.

Syntax:
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {}
}

Example:
class MyThread extends Thread {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running");
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        MyThread t = new MyThread();
        t.start();
    }
}

Definition:
Synchronization is used to control access of multiple threads to shared resources.

Syntax:
synchronized void method() {}

Example:
class Table {
    synchronized void print(int n) {
        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            System.out.println(n * i);
        }
    }
}

Definition:
Stack memory stores method calls and local variables. It works in LIFO (Last In First Out) order.

Syntax:
(No direct syntax, memory concept)

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 10; // stored in stack
        System.out.println(a);
    }
}

Definition:
Heap memory stores objects and instance variables.

Syntax:
ClassName obj = new ClassName();

Example:
class Student {
    int id = 101;
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Student s = new Student(); // stored in heap
        System.out.println(s.id);
    }
}

Definition:
Garbage collection is a process that removes unused objects automatically.

Syntax:
System.gc();

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Main obj = new Main();
        obj = null; // eligible for garbage collection
        System.gc();
    }
}

Definition:
Class loader loads class files into JVM memory.

Syntax:
(No direct syntax)

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Class loaded by JVM");
    }
}

Definition:
A package is a group of related classes and interfaces.

Syntax:
package mypack;

Example:
package mypack;

class Demo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println("Package example");
    }
}

Definition:
File handling is used to read and write files.

Syntax:
File file = new File("file.txt");

Example:
import java.io.File;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        File file = new File("test.txt");
        System.out.println(file.exists());
    }
}

Definition:
BufferedReader is used to read text efficiently from input stream.

Syntax:
BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));

Example:
import java.io.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        BufferedReader br = new BufferedReader(new InputStreamReader(System.in));
        System.out.println("Enter text:");
        String name = br.readLine();
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

Definition:
Scanner class is used to take input from user.

Syntax:
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);

Example:
import java.util.Scanner;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
        System.out.println("Enter number:");
        int num = sc.nextInt();
        System.out.println(num);
    }
}

Definition:
Serialization converts an object into byte stream for storage or transfer.

Syntax:
class ClassName implements Serializable {}

Example:
import java.io.Serializable;

class Student implements Serializable {
    int id = 101;
}

Definition:
Java Collections is a framework that provides classes and interfaces to store and manipulate data.

Syntax:
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

Example:
import java.util.ArrayList;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add(10);
        list.add(20);
        System.out.println(list);
    }
}

Definition:
Constructor overloading means having multiple constructors with different parameters in the same class.

Syntax:
class Demo {
    Demo() {}
    Demo(int a) {}
}

Example:
class Demo {
    Demo() {
        System.out.println("Default constructor");
    }

    Demo(int a) {
        System.out.println("Value: " + a);
    }

    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Demo d1 = new Demo();
        Demo d2 = new Demo(10);
    }
}

Definition:
String is a sequence of characters used to store text.

Syntax:
String str = "Hello";

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        String name = "Java";
        System.out.println(name);
    }
}

Definition:
StringBuilder is used to create mutable (modifiable) strings.

Syntax:
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Java");
        sb.append(" Programming");
        System.out.println(sb);
    }
}

Definition:
String = immutable
StringBuilder = mutable

Syntax:
String s = "A";
StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("A");

Example:
String s = "Hello";
s.concat(" World");

StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("Hello");
sb.append(" World");

Definition:
ArrayList is a resizable array in Java (from Collections Framework).

Syntax:
ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();

Example:
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        ArrayList<Integer> list = new ArrayList<>();
        list.add(10);
        list.add(20);
        System.out.println(list);
    }
}

Definition:
LinkedList is a data structure where elements are stored in nodes linked together.

Syntax:
LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();

Example:
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        LinkedList<Integer> list = new LinkedList<>();
        list.add(100);
        list.add(200);
        System.out.println(list);
    }
}

Definition:
HashMap stores data in key-value pairs.

Syntax:
HashMap<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();

Example:
import java.util.*;

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        HashMap<Integer, String> map = new HashMap<>();
        map.put(1, "Java");
        map.put(2, "Python");
        System.out.println(map);
    }
}

Definition:
ArrayList → fast access
LinkedList → fast insertion/deletion

Syntax:
ArrayList<Integer> a = new ArrayList<>();
LinkedList<Integer> b = new LinkedList<>();

Definition:
final keyword is used to restrict modification of variable, method, or class.

Syntax:
final int a = 10;

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        final int x = 100;
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

Definition:
A final method cannot be overridden.

Syntax:
final void show() {}

Example:
class A {
    final void show() {
        System.out.println("Final method");
    }
}

Definition:
A final class cannot be inherited.

Syntax:
final class A {}

Example:
final class A {
    void display() {
        System.out.println("Final class");
    }
}

Definition:
Packages are of two types:
Built-in packages
User-defined packages

Syntax:
import java.util.*;

Example:
import java.util.Scanner;

class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
    }
}

Definition:
Access modifiers define visibility of classes, methods, and variables.

Syntax:
public, private, protected, default

Example:
class Demo {
    private int a = 10;
}

Definition:
break → exits loop
continue → skips current iteration

Syntax:
break;
continue;

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        for(int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
            if(i == 3)
                continue;

            System.out.println(i);
        }
    }
}

Definition:
Type promotion automatically converts smaller data type into larger data type during expression evaluation.

Syntax:
int + float → float

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        int a = 10;
        float b = 5.5f;
        float result = a + b;
        System.out.println(result);
    }
}

Definition:
It allows passing values to a Java program at runtime through terminal.

Syntax:
public static void main(String[] args)

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(args[0]);
    }
}

Definition:
Wrapper classes convert primitive types into objects.

Syntax:
Integer i = 10;

Example:
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Integer x = 100;
        System.out.println(x);
    }
}

Definition:
Enum is used to define a fixed set of constants.

Syntax:
enum Day { MON, TUE, WED }

Example:
enum Day { MON, TUE, WED }
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        System.out.println(Day.MON);
    }
}

Definition:
A class defined inside another class.

Syntax:
class Outer { class Inner {} }

Example:
class Outer {
    class Inner {
        void show() {
            System.out.println("Inner class");
        }
    }
}

Definition:
A class without a name used for one-time implementation.

Syntax:
new Class() { }

Example:
interface A { void show(); }
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A obj = new A() {
            public void show() {
                System.out.println("Anonymous class");
            }
        };
        obj.show();
    }
}

Definition:
Interface with only one abstract method.

Syntax:
@FunctionalInterface

Example:
@FunctionalInterface
interface A {
    void show();
}

Definition:
Short way to implement functional interface.

Syntax:
() -> {}

Example:
interface A { void show(); }
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        A obj = () -> System.out.println("Lambda Expression");
        obj.show();
    }
}

Definition:
Runnable is used to create threads without extending Thread class.

Syntax:
class A implements Runnable

Example:
class MyTask implements Runnable {
    public void run() {
        System.out.println("Thread running");
    }
}

Definition:
A situation where two threads wait forever for each other.

Example:
class Demo {
    static final Object A = new Object();
    static final Object B = new Object();
}

Definition:
Used to lock only part of method instead of full method.

Syntax:
synchronized(obj) { }

Example:
class Table {
    void print(int n) {
        synchronized(this) {
            for(int i=1;i<=5;i++)
                System.out.println(n*i);
        }
    }
}

Definition:
Used for reading and writing data in files.

Syntax:
FileInputStream, FileOutputStream

Example:
import java.io.*;
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        FileInputStream fis = new FileInputStream("a.txt");
    }
}

Definition:
Serialization → object → file
Deserialization → file → object

Syntax:
implements Serializable

Example:
import java.io.*;
class Student implements Serializable {
    int id = 101;
}

Definition:
Used to inspect classes, methods at runtime.

Syntax:
Class.forName()

Example:
class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) throws Exception {
        Class c = Class.forName("java.lang.String");
        System.out.println(c.getName());
    }
}

Definition:
Used before object is destroyed.

Syntax:
protected void finalize()

Example:
class Demo {
    protected void finalize() {
        System.out.println("Object destroyed");
    }
}
